<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Document</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/formula.css">

    <!-- Import Material Design Icons -->
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/icon?family=Material+Icons" rel="stylesheet">
    
    <!-- Import Material Design Symbols (the new version of icons?) -->
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Material+Symbols+Outlined" rel="stylesheet" />


    <!-- Import Roboto Google Font -->
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto:ital,wght@0,100;0,300;0,400;0,500;0,700;0,900;1,100;1,300;1,400;1,500;1,700;1,900&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">

    <!-- Import Material Design Components CSS -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://unpkg.com/material-components-web@latest/dist/material-components-web.min.css">
    <script src="https://unpkg.com/material-components-web@latest/dist/material-components-web.min.js"></script>
    
</head>

<body>
    <!-- Header -->
    <div class="header">
        <div class="header-content">
            <span class="material-icons close-icon">close</span>
            <h1>Deriving Our Formula</h1>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Toolbar -->
    <div class="progress">
        <div class="progress-content">
            <span class="material-symbols-outlined toolbox-icon">calculate</span>
            <span class="material-symbols-outlined roadmap-icon">conversion_path</span>
            <svg class="progress-bar" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" height="10" fill="none">
                <rect width="100%" height="10" rx="5" fill="#ACB2ED"/>
            </svg>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Content -->
    <div class="instruction fd-summary">
        <h2>Summary</h2>
        <p>Let's do a quick review of how to find the formulas we'll use in the Figure of Merit of a Galvanometer Lab.</p>
        <p>Using the half-deflection method, we take two measurements to find the figure of merit (k).</p>
        <p>But, why can't we find k with just one measurement?</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Next Button -->
    <div class="button-container">
        <button class="mdc-button mdc-button--outline">
            <span class="mdc-button__label">Next</span>
        </button>
    </div>
        
</body>

</html>